# Getting Started: OAuth2 Authentication Flow in React

> **Audience:** Mid-level frontend developers familiar with React and basic HTTP concepts.
> **Prerequisites:** Node.js ≥18, a registered OAuth2 application with your provider (client ID, redirect URI configured), and an existing React app (Vite or CRA).

---

## Overview

This tutorial implements the **Authorization Code Flow with PKCE** (Proof Key for Code Exchange) — the correct flow for public clients like SPAs. We deliberately avoid the **Implicit Flow**, which is deprecated per [OAuth 2.0 Security Best Current Practice (RFC 9700)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc9700).

```
Browser          Your React App          Authorization Server          Your API
   │──── login click ──▶│                        │                       │
   │                    │── redirect w/ PKCE ──▶ │                       │
   │◀───────────────────│── auth code ──────────▶│                       │
   │                    │◀── access token ───────│                       │
   │                    │──── API request w/ Bearer token ──────────────▶│
```

---

## Step 1 — Install Dependencies

```bash
npm install oidc-client-ts react-oidc-context
```

| Package | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `oidc-client-ts` | Handles PKCE generation, token storage, and silent renewal |
| `react-oidc-context` | React context/hooks wrapper around `oidc-client-ts` |

> **Why not roll your own?** PKCE requires cryptographically secure random generation and precise code-verifier hashing (SHA-256). Libraries handle this correctly. Manual implementations frequently introduce vulnerabilities.

---

## Step 2 — Configure Your Environment Variables

Create or update `.env.local` at your project root. **Never commit this file.**

```bash
# .env.local
VITE_AUTH_AUTHORITY=https://auth.yourprovider.com
VITE_AUTH_CLIENT_ID=your-client-id
VITE_AUTH_REDIRECT_URI=http://localhost:5173/callback
VITE_AUTH_POST_LOGOUT_URI=http://localhost:5173
VITE_AUTH_SCOPES=openid profile email
```

Add `.env.local` to `.gitignore` if it isn't already:

```bash
echo ".env.local" >> .gitignore
```

> ⚠️ **Security note:** Client secrets must **never** appear here. In Authorization Code + PKCE flow for SPAs, no client secret is used — this is by design.

---

## Step 3 — Create the Auth Configuration

```ts
// src/auth/authConfig.ts
import { WebStorageStateStore } from 'oidc-client-ts';

export const authConfig = {
  authority: import.meta.env.VITE_AUTH_AUTHORITY,
  client_id: import.meta.env.VITE_AUTH_CLIENT_ID,
  redirect_uri: import.meta.env.VITE_AUTH_REDIRECT_URI,
  post_logout_redirect_uri: import.meta.env.VITE_AUTH_POST_LOGOUT_URI,
  scope: import.meta.env.VITE_AUTH_SCOPES,

  // PKCE is enforced by default in oidc-client-ts
  response_type: 'code',

  // Store tokens in sessionStorage, not localStorage
  // localStorage persists across tabs and survives browser restarts —
  // a stolen XSS payload can silently exfiltrate tokens.
  userStore: new WebStorageStateStore({ store: window.sessionStorage }),

  // Attempt silent token renewal 60 seconds before expiry
  automaticSilentRenew: true,
  silentRequestTimeoutInSeconds: 10,
};
```

> ⚠️ **Token storage trade-offs:**
> - `sessionStorage` — cleared on tab close; safer against persistent XSS
> - `localStorage` — survives restarts; higher XSS risk
> - In-memory — most secure; user must re-authenticate on refresh
>
> Match your choice to your app's security requirements and UX tolerance.

---

## Step 4 — Wrap Your App with the Auth Provider

```tsx
// src/main.tsx
import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client';
import { AuthProvider } from 'react-oidc-context';
import App from './App';
import { authConfig } from './auth/authConfig';

const onSigninCallback = (): void => {
  // Remove the auth code and state from the URL after the callback is processed.
  // Leaving them in the URL is a security risk — they can leak via Referer headers.
  window.history.replaceState({}, document.title, window.location.pathname);
};

ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root')!).render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <AuthProvider {...authConfig} onSigninCallback={onSigninCallback}>
      <App />
    </AuthProvider>
  </React.StrictMode>
);
```

---

## Step 5 — Handle the Redirect Callback Route

Your provider will redirect to `VITE_AUTH_REDIRECT_URI` with an authorization code. That URL must be rendered by your app to complete the exchange.

```tsx
// src/pages/AuthCallback.tsx
import { useEffect } from 'react';
import { useAuth } from 'react-oidc-context';
import { useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom';

export default function AuthCallback() {
  const auth = useAuth();
  const navigate = useNavigate();

  useEffect(() => {
    // The AuthProvider processes the callback automatically.
    // Once authentication is complete, redirect to the intended destination.
    if (!auth.isLoading && auth.isAuthenticated) {
      navigate('/', { replace: true });
    }

    if (!auth.isLoading && auth.error) {
      console.error('Auth callback error:', auth.error);
      navigate('/login', { replace: true });
    }
  }, [auth.isLoading, auth.isAuthenticated, auth.error, navigate]);

  if (auth.isLoading) return <p>Completing sign-in…</p>;
  if (auth.error) return <p>Authentication failed: {auth.error.message}</p>;

  return null;
}
```

Register this route in your router:

```tsx
// src/App.tsx (excerpt)
import { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route } from 'react-router-dom';
import AuthCallback from './pages/AuthCallback';
import ProtectedPage from './pages/ProtectedPage';

export default function App() {
  return (
    <BrowserRouter>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/callback" element={<AuthCallback />} />
        <Route path="/" element={<ProtectedPage />} />
      </Routes>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
}
```

---

## Step 6 — Build a Protected Route Guard

```tsx
// src/auth/RequireAuth.tsx
import { useAuth } from 'react-oidc-context';
import type { ReactNode } from 'react';

interface RequireAuthProps {
  children: ReactNode;
}

export default function RequireAuth({ children }: RequireAuthProps) {
  const auth = useAuth();

  if (auth.isLoading) {
    return <div aria-live="polite">Loading authentication…</div>;
  }

  if (auth.error) {
    return (
      <div role="alert">
        Authentication error: {auth.error.message}.{' '}
        <button onClick={() => auth.signinRedirect()}>Retry</button>
      </div>
    );
  }

  if (!auth.isAuthenticated) {
    // Trigger login redirect — do not render protected content
    auth.signinRedirect();
    return null;
  }

  return <>{children}</>;
}
```

Use it around any protected page:

```tsx
// src/App.tsx (updated excerpt)
<Route
  path="/dashboard"
  element={
    <RequireAuth>
      <Dashboard />
    </RequireAuth>
  }
/>
```

---

## Step 7 — Make Authenticated API Requests

Always attach the access token as a `Bearer` token in the `Authorization` header — **never** in query parameters, where it would appear in server logs and browser history.

```ts
// src/api/apiClient.ts
import { User } from 'oidc-client-ts';
import { authConfig } from '../auth/authConfig';

function getUser(): User | null {
  // Mirror the key oidc-client-ts uses internally
  const key = `oidc.user:${authConfig.authority}:${authConfig.client_id}`;
  const raw = sessionStorage.getItem(key);
  if (!raw) return null;
  return User.fromStorageString(raw);
}

export async function apiFetch(
  endpoint: string,
  options: RequestInit = {}
): Promise<Response> {
  const user = getUser();

  if (!user || user.expired) {
    throw new Error('User is not authenticated or token has expired.');
  }

  const response = await fetch(`https://api.yourdomain.com${endpoint}`, {
    ...options,
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/json',
      Authorization: `Bearer ${user.access_token}`,
      ...options.headers,
    },
  });

  if (response.status === 401) {
    // Token may have been revoked server-side — trigger re-authentication
    throw new Error('Unauthorized. Please sign in again.');
  }

  return response;
}
```

Usage in a component:

```tsx
const data = await apiFetch('/api/profile');
```

---

## Step 8 — Add Login and Logout Controls

```tsx
// src/components/AuthControls.tsx
import { useAuth } from 'react-oidc-context';

export default function AuthControls() {
  const auth = useAuth();

  if (auth.isAuthenticated) {
    return (
      <div>
        <span>Signed in as {auth.user?.profile.email}</span>
        <button
          onClick={() =>
            auth.signoutRedirect({
              post_logout_redirect_uri: import.meta.env.VITE_AUTH_POST_LOGOUT_URI,
            })
          }
        >
          Sign Out
        </button>
      </div>
    );
  }

  return (
    <button onClick={() => auth.signinRedirect()}>
      Sign In
    </button>
  );
}
```

---

## Step 9 — Verify the Full Flow

Run your app and walk through this checklist:

```
□ Clicking "Sign In" redirects to your provider's login page
□ After login, the browser returns to /callback
□ The URL is cleaned (no ?code= or ?state= visible) after redirect
□ The user's profile info renders correctly
□ Refreshing the page keeps the user authenticated (session intact)
□ Clicking "Sign Out" clears the session and redirects properly
□ Protected routes redirect unauthenticated users to login
□ Network tab shows Authorization: Bearer <token> on API calls
□ No tokens appear in localStorage (check Application tab in DevTools)
```

---

## Common Errors and Fixes

| Error | Likely Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| `redirect_uri_mismatch` | URI in code ≠ URI registered with provider | Ensure exact match including trailing slash |
| `invalid_grant` | Auth code already used or expired | Codes are single-use; check for double-rendering (React StrictMode) |
| `CORS error` on token endpoint | Provider not whitelisting your origin | Configure allowed origins in provider dashboard |
| Token not renewing silently | Silent renew iframe blocked by CSP or cookies | Ensure `frame-src` CSP directive and `SameSite=None; Secure` on session cookies |
| User `null` after refresh | Incorrect storage key lookup | Verify `authority` and `client_id` match exactly in key construction |

---

## What's Next

- **[Refresh Token Rotation →]** For stricter security, request `offline_access` scope and rotate refresh tokens
- **[Role-Based Access Control →]** Parse claims from `auth.user?.profile` to conditionally render UI
- **[Token Introspection →]** Validate tokens server-side rather than trusting expiry timestamps alone
- **[Content Security Policy →]** Restrict `script-src` to mitigate XSS, which is the primary threat vector against token storage

---

> **Security reminder:** OAuth2 in a SPA is secure when implemented correctly. The two most common mistakes are storing tokens in `localStorage` without understanding the XSS risk, and skipping PKCE. This tutorial avoids both. Always review the [OAuth 2.0 for Browser-Based Applications BCP](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/draft-ietf-oauth-browser-based-apps) when your threat model changes.

# React Auth Context Provider for Next.js

## Architecture Overview

This implementation handles three core challenges:
1. **Hydration mismatch** — server renders without localStorage access; client must sync carefully
2. **Stale state** — token expiry must be checked on mount and on focus
3. **Race conditions** — concurrent auth operations need safe state transitions

---

## File Structure

```
src/
├── lib/
│   ├── auth/
│   │   ├── types.ts
│   │   ├── storage.ts        # Encapsulated localStorage operations
│   │   ├── token.ts          # JWT decode + expiry utilities
│   │   └── context.tsx       # Provider + hook
│   └── api/
│       └── auth.ts           # Auth API calls
└── app/
    └── layout.tsx            # Provider mounted here
```

---

## Implementation

### `src/lib/auth/types.ts`

```typescript
export interface User {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  name: string;
  roles: string[];
  avatarUrl?: string;
}

export interface AuthTokens {
  accessToken: string;
  refreshToken: string;
  expiresAt: number; // Unix timestamp (ms)
}

export type AuthStatus = "idle" | "loading" | "authenticated" | "unauthenticated";

export interface AuthState {
  status: AuthStatus;
  user: User | null;
  tokens: AuthTokens | null;
  /**
   * True only after the client has reconciled localStorage.
   * Guards against hydration mismatches — do NOT render auth-
   * dependent UI until this is true.
   */
  isHydrated: boolean;
}

export interface AuthContextValue extends AuthState {
  login: (email: string, password: string) => Promise<void>;
  logout: () => Promise<void>;
  refreshSession: () => Promise<boolean>;
  hasRole: (role: string) => boolean;
}
```

---

### `src/lib/auth/storage.ts`

```typescript
/**
 * Isolated localStorage adapter.
 *
 * - Never throws to the caller — all errors are swallowed and logged.
 * - Returns null instead of throwing on missing/corrupt data.
 * - Versioned key prevents stale data from previous app schemas.
 */

import type { AuthTokens, User } from "./types";

const STORAGE_VERSION = "v1";
const KEYS = {
  tokens: `auth:${STORAGE_VERSION}:tokens`,
  user: `auth:${STORAGE_VERSION}:user`,
} as const;

function safeGet<T>(key: string): T | null {
  try {
    const raw = localStorage.getItem(key);
    if (!raw) return null;
    return JSON.parse(raw) as T;
  } catch (err) {
    console.warn(`[AuthStorage] Failed to read "${key}":`, err);
    return null;
  }
}

function safeSet(key: string, value: unknown): void {
  try {
    localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(value));
  } catch (err) {
    // Handles QuotaExceededError, SecurityError in private browsing, etc.
    console.warn(`[AuthStorage] Failed to write "${key}":`, err);
  }
}

function safeRemove(key: string): void {
  try {
    localStorage.removeItem(key);
  } catch {
    // Silently fail — storage may already be inaccessible
  }
}

export const AuthStorage = {
  getTokens: () => safeGet<AuthTokens>(KEYS.tokens),
  setTokens: (tokens: AuthTokens) => safeSet(KEYS.tokens, tokens),

  getUser: () => safeGet<User>(KEYS.user),
  setUser: (user: User) => safeSet(KEYS.user, user),

  clear: () => {
    safeRemove(KEYS.tokens);
    safeRemove(KEYS.user);
  },

  /**
   * Load a consistent snapshot of both values atomically.
   * If either is missing or tokens are expired, treat as unauthenticated.
   */
  loadSession: (): { user: User; tokens: AuthTokens } | null => {
    const tokens = safeGet<AuthTokens>(KEYS.tokens);
    const user = safeGet<User>(KEYS.user);

    if (!tokens || !user) return null;
    if (Date.now() >= tokens.expiresAt) {
      // Access token expired — caller decides whether to refresh
      return null;
    }

    return { tokens, user };
  },
};
```

